- The Prototype Pattern is a Creational Design Pattern that creates new objects by copying (cloning) 
an existing object instead of creating a new one from scratch.
- The Prototype Pattern is used when creating an object is expensive or complex. Instead of creating a new 
object every time, we clone an existing object and modify it if needed.

- Sometimes creating an object takes a lot of time because it requires loading data from a database, reading 
configuration files, or performing complex initialization. Creating the same object repeatedly is inefficient.

- The Prototype Pattern solves this problem by creating one fully initialized object, called the prototype, 
and then creating new objects by cloning it. Cloning is usually much faster than constructing a new object 
from scratch. This improves performance and avoids repeating expensive initialization logic.

[Why do we need Prototype Pattern?]
- Suppose you're developing a game.

Creating an enemy involves:
    Loading image
    Loading weapon
    Loading animations
    Loading AI behavior

Creating every enemy from scratch:
    Enemy
      ↓
    Load Image
      ↓
    Load Weapon
      ↓
    Load AI
      ↓
    Initialize

- This happens for every enemy. Which is Very slow.

#Problem Without Prototype
- Suppose creating one enemy takes 2 seconds. Need to create 100 enemies.
- 100 × 2 seconds = 200 seconds

- Most of the data is identical. Huge waste of time.

#Solution
- Create one enemy and Clone it.

    Original Enemy
      ↓
    Clone
      ↓
    Enemy 1,
    Enemy 2,
    Enemy 3,
    Enemy 4,

- Only change unique properties like
    Position
    Health
    Name

Everything else is copied.





















